    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-21T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-21T04:00:00-05:00" n="198"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d198">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">874.51/5–2145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Barnes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-21T11:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 21, 1945—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 21—9:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>258. A remark by Minister of Finance<note n="50" xml:id="d198fn1">Petko
                        Stoyanov.</note> the other evening seems interesting enough to telegraph. He
                    said it now costs Bulgarian Govt three and one half billion leva a month in
                    addition to the regular budget to support Soviet troops of occupation and the
                    Bulgarian Army at front and that these expenditures will have a disastrous
                    effect on Bulgarian economy if they continue indefinitely beyond cessation of
                    hostilities in Europe. Repeated to Moscow as No. 123.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Barnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
